NOTES_RUTH = {
    1: {
        1: 'HISTORICAL: "In the days when the judges governed" (bimey shephot hashophetim) — places Ruth in the period of Judges, a time of spiritual decline and moral chaos (Judg. 21:25). The famine echoes God\'s covenant warnings (Deut. 28:23-24). Bethlehem (beth lechem = "house of bread") having no bread is deeply ironic.',
        2: 'HEBREW: Elimelech (\'eli-melekh) = "my God is King." Naomi (na\'omi) = "pleasant, delightful." Mahlon = "sickness" and Chilion = "wasting, destruction" — their names foreshadow their deaths. Ephrathites links them to the clan of Ephrath, the ancient name for Bethlehem (Gen. 35:19).',
        6: 'HEBREW: "The LORD had visited" (paqad YHWH) — paqad carries the sense of divine intervention, a purposeful act of attention. The same word describes God\'s visitation to Sarah (Gen. 21:1) and Israel in Egypt (Exod. 4:31).',
        8: 'HEBREW: "Deal kindly" (ya\'aseh YHWH \'immakhem chesed) — first occurrence of chesed in Ruth. Chesed = covenant loyalty, steadfast love, lovingkindness. This word drives the entire book. Naomi prays the LORD would show the same chesed to them that they showed to the dead.',
        13: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The hand of the LORD has gone forth against me" — Naomi interprets her suffering as divine judgment. Her theology is incomplete but honest. She acknowledges God\'s sovereignty even in suffering, a raw faith that will be redeemed by the end of the book.',
        14: 'HEBREW: "Ruth clung to her" (Ruth davqah bah) — davaq is the same verb used in Gen. 2:24 for a man "cleaving" to his wife. It denotes permanent, covenantal bonding. Orpah\'s kiss is farewell; Ruth\'s clinging is covenant.',
        16: 'THEOLOGICAL: Ruth\'s confession — "your people shall be my people, and your God, my God" — is one of the greatest statements of covenant loyalty (chesed) in all of scripture. A Moabite woman voluntarily binds herself to the God of Israel. This is a conversion statement: Ruth forsakes Chemosh for YHWH. She uses covenant language that mirrors marriage and adoption formulas in the ancient Near East.',
        17: 'HEBREW: "Thus may the LORD do to me, and more also" (koh ya\'aseh YHWH li wekhoh yosif) — a self-imprecatory oath formula. Ruth invokes YHWH by name, confirming her conversion. She binds herself to Israel\'s God even unto death and burial — a total, irrevocable commitment.',
        20: 'HEBREW: Naomi (na\'omi = "pleasant") asks to be called Mara (mara = "bitter"). The Almighty (Shaddai) — she uses this ancient patriarchal name for God, emphasizing His power over her fate. Her bitterness is the low point from which God\'s redemption will lift her.',
        22: 'CHRIST TYPOLOGY: Ruth arrives in Bethlehem "at the beginning of barley harvest" — the season of Passover and Firstfruits. This Moabite woman entering God\'s provision in Bethlehem ("house of bread") at harvest time foreshadows the inclusion of Gentiles in God\'s redemptive plan. Bethlehem will later be the birthplace of David and of Christ (Mic. 5:2; Matt. 2:1).',
    },
    2: {
        1: 'HEBREW: "A kinsman" (meyudda\') and "a man of great wealth" (\'ish gibbor chayil) — gibbor chayil means a mighty man of valor/substance, denoting both wealth and character. Boaz\'s name (bo\'az) likely means "in him is strength." He is introduced before he appears, as the answer to the problem before it is stated.',
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: The gleaning laws of Lev. 19:9-10 and Deut. 24:19-22 specifically protect the poor, the stranger, the orphan, and the widow — Ruth is all of these at once. God\'s law makes provision for the marginalized through the generosity of the landowner.',
        10: 'HEBREW: "A foreigner" (nokhriyyah) — Ruth uses the strongest term for outsider, not ger (resident alien) but nokhri (true foreigner with no legal standing). She is acutely aware of her status. Yet God\'s law specifically includes her.',
        12: 'CHRIST TYPOLOGY: "Under whose wings (kanaf) you have come to take refuge" — kanaf means wing or edge of a garment. The image is of a bird sheltering its young (Ps. 91:4; Matt. 23:37). In 3:9 Ruth will ask Boaz to spread his kanaf over her — the human outworking of divine refuge. Boaz becomes the instrument of the very blessing he pronounced. This is a type of Christ who is both the one who blesses and the blessing itself.',
        14: 'THEOLOGICAL: Boaz invites Ruth to his table — "eat of the bread and dip your piece in the vinegar." She eats, is satisfied, and has leftovers. The abundance and personal generosity of Boaz exceed the requirements of the gleaning law. Grace goes beyond what the law demands.',
        20: 'HEBREW: "One of our redeemers" (migoaleinu) — first explicit use of go\'el (kinsman-redeemer) in Ruth. The go\'el had legal responsibilities: redeem sold property (Lev. 25:25), redeem a relative from slavery (Lev. 25:47-49), avenge blood (Num. 35:19), and marry a brother\'s widow (Deut. 25:5-10). Naomi now sees God\'s hand at work: chesed "to the living and to the dead."',
    },
    3: {
        1: 'HEBREW: "Security" (manoach) — from the root nuach, meaning rest, settled security. Related to the "rest" (menuchah) Naomi prayed for in 1:9. Naomi is now actively working to secure the redemption she earlier despaired of.',
        4: 'HEBREW: "Uncover his feet" (wegillit margelotav) — margelot is related to regel (foot). The act has symbolic significance: feet/sandals are connected to legal transactions of land and marriage (cf. 4:7-8; Deut. 25:9). This is not seduction but a legal claim upon the kinsman-redeemer.',
        9: 'CHRIST TYPOLOGY: "Spread your wing (kanaf) over your maidservant, for you are a redeemer (go\'el)" — Ruth directly echoes Boaz\'s own blessing from 2:12, where he spoke of God\'s wings (kanaf). She asks Boaz to be the human fulfillment of the divine protection he invoked. The go\'el must be a kinsman (Boaz is), must be willing (Boaz is), and must be able to pay the price (Boaz can). Christ fulfills all three: He became our kinsman through incarnation (Heb. 2:14), was willing (John 10:18), and paid the full price (1 Pet. 1:18-19).',
        10: 'HEBREW: "Your last kindness" (chasdekh ha\'acharon) — chesed again. Ruth\'s "first" chesed was loyalty to Naomi (1:16-17); her "last" is seeking the proper kinsman-redeemer rather than a younger man. She acts within the covenant structure rather than for personal advantage.',
        11: 'HEBREW: "A woman of excellence" (\'eshet chayil) — the same phrase used in Prov. 31:10 ("an excellent wife"). Chayil parallels Boaz\'s own description as \'ish gibbor chayil (2:1). They are matched in character.',
        13: 'THEOLOGICAL: "As the LORD lives" (chay YHWH) — Boaz swears by the living God. His commitment to redeem is an oath, not merely a promise. The legal process must be followed — the nearer kinsman has first right — but Boaz commits himself irrevocably if that kinsman declines.',
        15: 'HEBREW: "Six measures of barley" — the unit is unspecified (not an ephah, which would be impossibly heavy). The six measures may symbolize incompleteness (six, not seven), pointing to the fullness of redemption still to come in chapter 4.',
    },
    4: {
        1: 'HEBREW: "Friend" (peloni \'almoni) — literally "so-and-so," a deliberate anonymity. The unnamed kinsman\'s refusal to redeem erases his name from memory, while Boaz\'s willingness to redeem makes his name eternal. The text enacts what it teaches: the one who will not redeem becomes nameless.',
        4: 'THEOLOGICAL: The nearer kinsman says "I will redeem" — he is willing when only land is involved. The test comes in verse 5-6 when the full cost is revealed. Partial willingness to redeem is not redemption at all.',
        5: 'HEBREW: "Raise up the name of the dead on his inheritance" (lehakim shem hammet \'al nachalato) — this combines the levirate duty (Deut. 25:5-6) with the land redemption law (Lev. 25:25). The redeemer must not only buy the land but marry the widow and produce an heir. The cost is total.',
        6: 'CHRIST TYPOLOGY: The nearer kinsman cannot redeem — "lest I ruin my own inheritance" (pen \'ashchit \'et nachalati). He counts the cost and declines. This is the law\'s limitation: it can identify what must be done but cannot provide the power to do it. The nearer kinsman represents the law, which is "weak through the flesh" (Rom. 8:3). Boaz, the kinsman who can and will redeem at full cost, is the type of Christ. The law could not redeem us; Christ could and did.',
        7: 'HEBREW: "Removed his sandal" (shalaf na\'alo) — the sandal ceremony is attested in Deut. 25:9-10. The sandal represents the right of possession over land (cf. Ps. 60:8, "over Edom I shall throw My shoe"). Transferring the sandal transfers the redemption right.',
        10: 'THEOLOGICAL: Boaz publicly acquires Ruth as his wife "to raise up the name of the dead." He does what the nearer kinsman would not. His public declaration before witnesses completes the legal redemption — land, widow, and name are all secured. The dead man\'s line will not be "cut off" (yikaret — the same root used for covenant cutting).',
        11: 'HEBREW: The blessing of Rachel and Leah invokes the matriarchs who built all of Israel. The mention of Perez, whom Tamar bore to Judah (Gen. 38), is significant — Tamar, like Ruth, was a foreign woman whose irregular actions led to the messianic line. Both are named in Christ\'s genealogy (Matt. 1:3, 5).',
        12: 'CHRIST TYPOLOGY: "May your house be like the house of Perez" — the elders\' blessing is prophetic. From Perez through Boaz and Ruth will come David, and from David, the Messiah. The genealogy at the end of Ruth (4:18-22) contains exactly ten names from Perez to David, a number of completeness.',
        13: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The LORD enabled her to conceive" (wayyitten YHWH lah herayon) — after the deaths of Mahlon and Chilion, after ten barren years in Moab, God directly intervenes. The same God who "visited His people" with bread (1:6) now visits Ruth with a child. Divine sovereignty bookends the story.',
        14: 'HEBREW: "A redeemer" (go\'el) — the women\'s blessing identifies the child Obed as a go\'el for Naomi. The redeemer is not Boaz but the son born through Boaz\'s redemption. The chain of redemption extends: God -> Boaz -> Obed -> the messianic line.',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Better to you than seven sons" — seven is the number of completeness in Hebrew thought. Ruth surpasses the ideal. A Moabite daughter-in-law exceeds in covenant loyalty what the fullest measure of Israelite sons could provide. This overturns ethnic boundaries by chesed.',
        16: 'CHRIST TYPOLOGY: "Naomi took the child and laid him in her lap (cheqah) and became his nurse (\'omenet)" — Naomi, who was empty (1:21), is now full. She who was bitter (Mara) is restored. The child on her lap completes her redemption. Naomi\'s arc from fullness to emptiness to restoration is a type of Israel\'s own story: blessed, exiled, redeemed.',
        17: 'HEBREW: "A son has been born to Naomi" — legally and covenantally, Obed continues Elimelech\'s and Mahlon\'s line through Naomi. Obed (\'oved) = "servant, worshiper." He is the father of Jesse (yishay), the father of David. From this threshing-floor encounter in Bethlehem comes Israel\'s greatest king, and through David, the Messiah (Matt. 1:5-6; Luke 3:32).',
        18: 'CHRIST TYPOLOGY: "These are the generations of Perez" (we\'elleh toledot Parets) — the toledot formula that structures Genesis (Gen. 2:4, 5:1, 6:9, etc.) appears here, linking Ruth back to the patriarchal narrative. The genealogy runs from Perez (Gen. 38, Judah\'s son by Tamar) through ten generations to David. This is the messianic line — Matt. 1:3-6 traces Christ\'s lineage through every name in this list. Ruth, the Moabite convert, stands in the direct ancestry of Jesus of Nazareth, the promised Messiah.',
        22: 'THEOLOGICAL: The book ends with David\'s name — the narrative climax. Everything in Ruth leads to this: the famine, the sojourn, the deaths, the return, the gleaning, the threshing floor, the gate, the marriage, the birth. All of it is God\'s sovereign orchestration of the messianic line. Ruth entered as a Moabite widow; she exits as the great-grandmother of David, the anointed king from whose line the Christ would come (2 Sam. 7:12-16; Isa. 11:1; Matt. 1:1).',
    },
}
